''Mat'' (lang-ru|мат; матерщи́на / ма́терный язы́к / мáтный язы́к, ''matershchina'' / ''materny yazyk'' / ''matny yazyk'') is the term for vulgarity|vulgar, obscene, or profanity|profane language in Russian language|Russian and some other Slavic language communities. The term ''mat'' derives from the Russian word for mother, a component of the key phrase "Ёб твою мать", yob tvoyu mat’ (fuck your mother).<ref>cite web| url= http://www.russki-mat.net/e/mat_VEvrofeyev.htm |title= The Unique Power of Russia’s Underground Language| last= Yerofeyev| first= Victor| date= October 12, 2003| website= russki-mat.net| access-date= </ref>

 Four pillars of mat 
''Mat'' has thousands of variations but ultimately centers on four pillars, the words ''khuy'' ("cock"); ''pizda'' ("cunt"); ''yebat’'' ("to fuck"); and ''blyad ("whore").<ref name=Putin>cite news| url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/putins-four-dirty-words|title=Putin's Four Dirty Words |first= David| last= Remnick|date= May 5, 2014|work= The New Yorker| access-date= September 6, 2017</ref>

= Khuy =
''Khuy'' (lang|ru|wikt:хуй|хуй; audio|Ru-Khuy.ogg|хуй) means cock, penis, or for an equivalent colloquial register: Dick (slang)|dick. The etymology of the term is unclear. Mainstream theories include from Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo European (PIE) *''ks-u-'', related to ''хвоя'' (''khvoya'', "pine needles"), attributed to Pederson, 1908;<ref>cite web| url= http://monstar.nnover.ru/blog/abuse/27651.html#Comments| title= Comments| website= monstar.nnover.ru| date= | access-date= </ref><ref>cite web| url= http://www.philology.ru/linguistics2/kovalyov-05.htm| website= philology.ru| trans-title= Russian Mat - Consequences of Destruction of the Taboo; Cultural taboos and their influence on the result of communication |author= Voronezh| year= 2005| pages= 184–197| language= Russian| title= РУССКИЙ МАТ - СЛЕДСТВИЕ УНИЧТОЖЕНИЯ ТАБУ (Культурные табу и их влияние на результат коммуникации.)| access-date= September 6, 2017</ref> from PIE *hau-, related to ''хвост'' (''khvost'', "tail"), attributed to Merlingen, 1955;  from Mongolian language|Mongolian хуй (''khui'', meaning "sheath" or "scabbard"). This was the etymology endorsed by the Soviet Union|Soviet government and attributed to Maxim Gorky, who claimed it was a loan word, imposed during the Mongol yoke. Alexander Gorokhovski suggests the derivation from the Latin language|Latin ''huic'' (lit. ''"for that"'', used on prescriptions for genital diseases) as a euphemism, because the old Russian ''"ud/uda"'' (from PIE root *''ud-'' meaning ''"up, out"'') became taboo in the mid-18th century.<ref>cite web| url= http://www.russki-mat.net/e/mat_Gorokhovski.htm | website= russki-mat.net| title= Матерщина: седая древность и цветущая юность| trans-title= Foul language: gray antiquity and blooming youth| first= A. | last= Gorokhovsky| language= Russian| access-date= September 6, 2017</ref> Currently, the first volume of the ''Great Dictionary of Mat'' by the Russian linguist and folklorist Alexei Plutser-Sarno treats only expressions with the stem ''хуй'' (''khuy''), numbering over 500 entries; 12 volumes are planned. Another theory is that it originates from the Greek word ''huios'' which means son.

= Pizda =
''Pizda&#769;'' (lang|ru|wikt:пизда́|пизда́ audio|Ru-Pizda.ogg|пизда) means cunt.<ref name=Putin/>

= Yebat' =
''Yeba&#769;t''' (lang|ru|wikt:ебать|еба́ть audio|Ru-Yebat.ogg|ебать) means fuck<ref name=Putin/>, also can be used as interjection expressing amazement. It comes from the Proto-Slavic ''jebati'' and Proto-Indo-European ''*h₃yebʰ-e-ti'', cf. Ancient Greek οἴφω (''oíphō'') "to live in a marriage" and Sanskrit यभति (''yabhati'')citation needed|date=August 2015

= Blyad'  =
''Blya&#769;d (lang|ru|wikt:блядь|блядь; audio|Ru-блядь.ogg|блядь) means Prostitution|whore.<ref name=Putin/>

 History and use 
Obscenities are among the earliest recorded attestations of the Russian language (the first written ''mat'' words date to the Middle Ages<ref>:ru:Берестяные грамоты#.D0.9E.D0.B1.D1.81.D1.86.D0.B5.D0.BD.D0.BD.D0.B0.D1.8F .D0.BB.D0.B5.D0.BA.D1.81.D0.B8.D0.BA.D0.B0 .D0.B2 .D0.B1.D0.B5.D1.80.D0.B5.D1.81.D1.82.D1.8F.D0.BD.D1.8B.D1.85 .D0.B3.D1.80.D0.B0.D0.BC.D0.BE.D1.82.D0.B0.D1.85|Obscene lexics in birch bark documents</ref>).

Mikhail Lermontov's 1834 ''"A Holiday in Peterhof"'' (''"Петергофский праздник"'') is one example of the usage of ''mat''.

